{{Infobox Organization |name = Agricultural and Food Research Council |bgcolor = #DDDDDD |abbreviation = AFRC |formation = 1983 |status = |purpose = Funding of UK agriculture and horticulture |headquarters = |region_served = {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[United Kingdom]] |type = |membership = |leader_title = |leader_name = |main_organ = |parent_organization = |affiliations = |budget = |website = }} The '''Agricultural and Food Research Council''' ('''AFRC''') was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[UK Research Councils|Research Council]] responsible for funding and managing scientific and technological developments in [[agriculture|farming]] and [[horticulture]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Contacts Directory|url=http://adlib.everysite.co.uk/adlib/defra/content.aspx?id=000IL3890W.16NTBY1IUSE1MQ|publisher=Department for Environment Food and Rural Affairs|accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 4690059 | year = 1973 | author1 = Burns | first1 = K. N. | title = The Agricultural Research Council | journal = Proceedings of the Royal Society of Medicine | volume = 66 | issue = 1 Pt 1 | pages = 5 | pmc = 1644363 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Agricultural Research 1931-1981|year=1981|publisher=Agricultural Research Council|isbn=0708401805}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 4722787 | year = 1973 | author1 = Burns | first1 = K. N. | title = Agricultural Research Council selection of topics for veterinary research | journal = The Veterinary Record | volume = 92 | issue = 13 | pages = 340–2 }}</ref>
==History== The AFRC was formed in 1983 from its predecessor, the '''Agricultural Research Council''' ('''ARC'''). It was replaced by the [[Biotechnology and Biological Sciences Research Council]] (BBSRC) as a result of government reorganisation in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biotechnology and Biological Sciences Research Council |url=http://www.rcuk.ac.uk/links/pages/bbsrc.aspx |publisher=BBSRC |accessdate=18 September 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023004435/http://www.rcuk.ac.uk/links/Pages/BBSRC.aspx |archivedate=23 October 2012 }}</ref> At that time Sir William Henderson who was secretary to the AFRC claimed that "agriculture was a success story" hence the AFRC could be closed and a new vision for research was envisaged in the creation of the BBSRC. With this shift in emphasis, there also followed the closure of several educational and research organisations as for example the internationally renowned [[Wye College]].
