==Religion==
The ''[[sociology of religion]]'' concerns the role of [[religion]] in [[society]]: practices, historical backgrounds, developments and universal themes.<ref>Kevin J. Christiano, et al., (2nd ed., 2008), Sociology of Religion: Contemporary Developments, Lanham, MD: Rowman & Littlefield Publishers. {{ISBN|978-0-7425-6111-3}}</ref> There is particular emphasis on the recurring role of religion in all societies and throughout recorded history. 
*{{cite book|last=Durkheim|first=Émile|author-link=Émile Durkheim |title=Les formes élémentaires de la vie religieuse |trans-title=[[The Elementary Forms of the Religious Life|The elementary forms of religious life]]|year=2008|origyear=1912 |publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-954012-9|edition=Reissue |translator=Carol Cosman |editor-first=Mark S. |editor-last=Cladis}}
*{{cite book|title=The Sacred Canopy: Elements of a Sociological Theory of Religion|first=Peter L. |last=Berger |author-link=Peter L. Berger|origyear=1967|year=2011|publisher=Open Road Media|isbn= 978-1-4532-1537-1}}{{sfn|Farganis|2011}}
*{{cite book|title=A Rumor of Angels: Modern Society and the Rediscovery of the Supernatural|first=Peter L. |last=Berger |author-mask=1|origyear=1970|year=2011|publisher=Open Road Media|isbn= 978-1-4532-1543-2}}

==Theory==
''[[Sociological theory|Sociological theories]]'' are complex [[theory|theoretical]] and [[methodology|methodological]] frameworks used to analyze and explain objects of social study. They facilitate organizing sociological knowledge.<ref name="Calhoun2002">{{cite book|author=Craig J. Calhoun|title=Classical sociological theory|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6mq-H3EcUx8C&pg=PA1|accessdate=2 March 2011|year=2002|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|isbn=978-0-631-21348-2|pages=1–}}</ref>

