===Rational choice theory===
''[[Rational choice theory]]'' models social behavior as the interaction of utility-maximizing individuals.

*[[James Samuel Coleman|Coleman, James S.]] (1990) ''Foundations of Social Theory''
*[[Mancur Olson|Olson, Mancur]] (1971) ''[[The Logic of Collective Action|The Logic of Collective Action: Public Goods and the Theory of Groups]]''. Harvard University Press. {{ISBN|0-674-53751-3}}

===Social network analysis===
''[[Social network|Social network analysis]]'' is structural approach to sociology that views norms and behaviors as embedded in chains of social relations. Makes use of [[network theory]].

*{{cite book|editor-last=Wellman|editor-first=Barry|editor-link=Barry Wellman |editor2-last=Berkowitz|editor2-first=S. D.|title=Social structures : a network approach|year=1991|origyear=1988 |publisher=Jai Press|location=Greenwich, Conn.|isbn=978-0-7623-0290-1|edition=1st publication, reprint}}
*{{cite book|last=Scott|first=John|author-link=John Scott (sociologist) |title=Social network analysis : a handbook|year=2000|origyear=1991 |publisher=Sage|location=London|isbn=978-0-7619-6339-4|edition=2nd}}
*{{cite book|last=Wasserman|first=Stanley|first2=Katherine |last2=Faust |title=Social network analysis : methods and applications|year=1999|origyear=1994 |publisher=Cambridge Univ. Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-521-38707-1|edition=Reprint.}}
:These three books present a good basic introduction to social network analysis. Scott is the most general and most recent. Wasserman and Faust presents thorough methodological coverage. Wellman and Berkowitz is the most readable, theoretical and provides many case studies.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}

