'''Fernando Emilio Novas''' is an [[Argentina|Argentine]] [[Paleontology|paleontologist]] working for the [[Comparative Anatomy]] Department of the [[Bernardino Rivadavia Natural Sciences Museum]] in [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]].<ref name="Cartage">[http://www.cartage.org.lb/en/themes/Biographies/MainBiographies/N/Novas/1.html Novas, Fernando E.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605215530/http://www.cartage.org.lb/en/themes/Biographies/MainBiographies/N/Novas/1.html |date=2011-06-05 }}</ref> Novas holds a [[PhD]] in [[Natural sciences]].

Working for the [[CONICET]], he described or co-described many [[dinosaur]]s, among them ''[[Abelisaurus]]'', ''[[Aniksosaurus]]'', ''[[Aragosaurus]]'', ''[[Austroraptor]]'', ''[[Chilesaurus]]'', ''[[Megaraptor]]'', ''[[Neuquenraptor]]'', ''[[Orkoraptor]]'', ''[[Patagonykus]]'', ''[[Unenlagia]]'', ''[[Araucanoraptor]]'', ''[[Skorpiovenator]]'', ''[[Tyrannotitan]]'', ''[[Talenkauen]]'', and ''[[Puertasaurus]]'', most from the [[Patagonia]] region of Argentina. [http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v522/n7556/full/nature14307.html' ''Chilesaurus diegosuarezi''] <ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1038/nature14307| title = An enigmatic plant-eating theropod from the Late Jurassic period of Chile| journal = Nature| year = 2015| last1 = Novas | first1 = F. E. | last2 = Salgado | first2 = L. | last3 = Suárez | first3 = M. | last4 = Agnolín | first4 = F. L. | last5 = Ezcurra | first5 = M. N. D. | last6 = Chimento | first6 = N. S. R. | last7 = de la Cruz | first7 = R. | last8 = Isasi | first8 = M. P. | last9 = Vargas | first9 = A. O. | last10 = Rubilar-Rogers | first10 = D. | pmid=25915021 | volume=522 | issue = 7556| pages=331–4}}</ref> made the cover of Nature magazine on June 18, 2015. 

