rial|controlled randomized experiments]] (before [[Ronald A. Fisher|Fisher]]). Invented [[optimal design]] for experiments on gravity, in which he "[[analysis of variance|corrected the means]]". He used [[correlation]], [[smoothing]], and improved the treatment of [[Peirce's criterion|outliers]]. Introduced terms "[[Confidence interval|confidence]]" and "[[Likelihood function|likelihood]]" (before [[Jerzy Neyman|Neyman]] and [[Ronald A. Fisher|Fisher]]). While largely a [[Frequency probability|frequentist]], Peirce's [[possible world semantics]] introduced the "[[propensity]]" theory of probability. See the historical books of [[Stephen Stigler]] || |- valign="top" | [[Francis Ysidro Edgeworth|Edgeworth, Francis Ysidro]] || Irish || 1845 || 1926 || Revived [[Exponential family|exponential families]] ([[Laplace transform]]s) in statistics. Extended [[Pierre-Simon Laplace|Laplace]]'s ([[asymptotic analysis|asymptotic]]) theory of [[Maximum likelihood|maximum-likelihood]] estimation. Introduced basic results on [[Fisher information|information]], which were extended and popularized by [[Ronald A. Fisher|R. A. Fisher]] || |- valign="top" | [[Karl Pearson|Pearson, Karl]] || English || 1857 || 1936 || Numerous innovations, including the development of the [[Pearson chi-squared test]] and the [[Pearson correlation]]. Founded the Biometrical Society and [[Biometrika]], the first journal of [[mathematical statistics]] and [[biometry]] || <ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.amstat.org/about/statisticiansinhistory/index.cfm?fuseaction=biosinfo&BioID=18 | title = Pearson, Karl | publisher = [[American Statistical Association]] | work = Statisticians in History | accessdate= }}</ref><ref name=PearsonUCL>{{cite web | year = | title = Karl Pearson (1857 - 1936) | publisher = Department of Statistical Science&nbsp;– [[University College London]] | url = http://www.ucl.ac.uk/stats/department/pearson.html | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080925065418/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/stats/department/pearson.html | archivedate = 25 September 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | year = 2003 | title = Karl Pearson | publisher = School of Mathematics and Statistics, [[University of St Andrews]] | url = http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/%7Ehistory/Biographies/Pearson.html | accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | year = 2008 | title = Karl Pearson: A Reader’s Guide | author = John Aldrich | publisher = [[University of Southampton]] | url = http://www.economics.soton.ac.uk/staff/aldrich/kpreader.htm | accessdate= }}</ref> |- valign="top" | [[Charles Spearman|Spearman, Charles]] || English || 1863 || 1945 || Extended the Pearson correlation coefficient to the [[Spearman's rank correlation coefficient]] || <ref>{{cite journal | year = 2003 | title = Charles Spearman: British Behavioral Scientist | journal = Human Nature Review | volume = 3 | pages = 114–118 | url = http://human-nature.com/nibbs/03/spearman.html | author = Williams, RH, Zimmerman, DW, Zumbo, BD & Ross, D}}</ref> |- valign="top" | [[William Sealy Gosset|Gosset, William Sealy]] (known as "Student") || English || 1876 || 1937 || Discovered the [[Student t distribution]] and invented the [[Student's t-test]] || <ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.economics.soton.ac.uk/staff/aldrich/Figures.htm#stu | work = Figures from the History of Probability and Statistics | title = William Sealy Gosset | publisher = [[University of Southampton]] | accessdate= }}</ref> |- valign="top" | [[Oskar Anderson|Anderson, Oskar Johann Viktor]] (also known as Anderson, Oskar Nikolaevich) || Russian, Bulgarian, German || 1887 || 1960 || A leading representative of the so-called Continental School of statistics. Invented the variate difference method for analyzing time series at the same time but independently from Gosset. A pioneer of random sampling in demographics and of quantitative methods applied to socio-economic sciences. || <ref name="statprob">{{cite encyclopedia | last1 = Strecker | first1 = Heinrich | last2 = Strecker | first2 = Rosemarie | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of Mathematics | title = Oskar Anderson | url = http://www.encyclopediaofmath.org/index.php?title=Anderson,_Oskar&oldid=39172 | publisher = Springer-Verlag GmbH, Heidelberg | year = 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{MacTutor|id=Anderson|title=Oskar Johann Viktor Anderson|date=May 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia | last = Sheynin | first = O.B. | title = Anderson, Oskar Johann Viktor | encyclopedia = [[Dictionary of Scientific Biography]] | volume = 1 | pages = 154–155 | publisher = Charles Scribner's Sons | location = New York | year = 1970 | isbn = 0-684-10114-9 | url = https://www.encyclopedia.com/science/dictionaries-thesauruses-pictures-and-press-releases/anderson-oskar-johann-viktor }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author1 = Jörg Siebels | author2 = Kerstin Nees | title=Oskar Anderson | work=Christian-Albrechts-Universität zu Kiel, Famous scholars from Kiel | url=http://www.uni-kiel.de/grosse-forscher/index.php?nid=anderson&lang=e | accessdate=2018-10-26}}</ref> |- valign="top" | [[Ronald Fisher|Fisher, Ronald]] || English || 1890 || 1962 || Wrote the textbooks and articles that defined the academic discipline of statistics, inspiring the creation of statistics departments at universities throughout the world. Systematized previous results with informative terminology, substantially improving previous results with mathematical analysis (and claims). Developed the [[analysis of variance]], clarified the method of [[maximum likelihood]] (without the uniform priors appearing in some previous versions), invented the concept of [[sufficient statistic]]s, developed Edgeworth's use of [[Exponential family|exponential families]] and [[Fisher information|information]], introducing ''observed'' [[Fisher information]], and many theoretical concepts and practical methods, particularly for the [[design of experiments]] || <ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.amstat.org/about/statisticiansinhistory/index.cfm?fuseaction=biosinfo&BioID=16 | title = Fisher, R.A. | publisher = [[American Statistical Association]] | work = Statisticians in History |accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.economics.soton.ac.uk/staff/aldrich/Figures.htm#fis | work = Figures from the History of Probability and Statistics | title = R.A. Fisher | publisher = [[University of Southampton]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.economics.soton.ac.uk/staff/aldrich/fisherguide/rafreader.htm | title = A Guide to R. A. Fisher | accessdate= }}</ref> |- valign="top" | [[Carlo Emilio Bonferroni|Bonferroni, Carlo Emilio]] || Italian || 1892 || 1960 || Invented the [[Bonferroni correction]] for [[multiple comparisons]] || |- valign="top" | [[Frank Wilcoxon|Wilcoxon, Frank]] || Irish-American || 1892 || 1965 || Invented two statistical tests: [[Wilcoxon rank-sum test]] and the [[Wilcoxon signed-rank test]] || |- valign="top" | [[Jerzy Neyman|Neyman, Jerzy]] || Polish-American || 1894 || 1981 || Discovered the [[confidence interval]] and co-developed the [[Neyman–Pearson lemma]] || <ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.amstat.org/about/statisticiansinhistory/index.cfm?fuseaction=biosinfo&BioID=11 | title = Neyman, Jerzy | publisher = [[American Statistical Association]] | work = Statisticians in History | accessdate= }}</ref> |- valign="top" | [[W. Edwards Deming|Deming, W. Edwards]] || American || 1900 || 1993 || Developed methods for statistical [[quality control]] || <ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.amstat.org/about/statisticiansinhistory/index.cfm?fuseaction=biosinfo&BioID=4 | title = Deming, W. Edwards| publisher = [[American Statistical Association]] | work = Statisticians in History | accessdate= }}</ref> |- valign="top" | [[Egon Pearson|Pearson, Egon]] || English || 1895 || 1980 || Co-developed the Neyman–Pearson lemma of statistical hypothesis testing || <ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.amstat.org/about/statisticiansinhistory/index.cfm?fuseaction=biosinfo&BioID=24 | title = Pearson, Egon S.| publisher = [[American Statistical Association]] | work = Statisticians in History | accessdate= }}</ref> |- valign="top" | [[Bruno de Finetti|Finetti, Bruno de]] || Italian || 1906 || 1985 || Pioneer of the "operational subjective" conception of probability. Used this as the basis for exposition of the Bayesian method of statistical analysis. Developed the representation theorem for [[exchangeable random variables]] showing that they are the basis of the IID model in statistics. || |- valign="top" | [[Maurice Kendall|Kendall, Maurice]] || English || 1907 || 1983 || Co-developed methods for assessing [[statistical randomness]]; invented [[Kendall tau rank correlation coefficient]] || |- valign="top" | [[John Tukey|Tukey, John]] || American || 1915 || 2000 || Jointly popularized [[Fast Fourier transform]]ation, pioneer of [[exploratory data analysis]] and [[statistical graphics|graphical presentation]] of data, developed the [[Resampling (statistics)#Jackknife|jackknife]] for [[random effects model|variance estimation]], invented the [[box plot]]. || <ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1098/rsbm.2003.0032 | url = http://journals.royalsociety.org/content/541x625k2vx6837v/fulltext.pdf | format = pdf | title = John Wilder Tukey. 16 June 1915&nbsp;– 26 July 2000 | year = 2003 | author = Mccullagh, Peter | journal = Biographical Memoirs of Fellows of the Royal Society | volume = 49 | pages = 537–555}}</ref> |- valign="top" | [[David Blackwell|Blackwell, David]] || American || 1919 || 2010 || Co-developed [[Rao-Blackwell theorem]] and wrote one of the first [[Bayesian statistics|Bayesian]] textbooks, ''Basic Statistics''. || <ref>{{cite web|author1=William Grimes|title=David Blackwell, Scholar of Probability, Dies at 91|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/17/education/17blackwell.html|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=24 September 2014|date=17 July 2010|quote=His “Basic Statistics” (1969) was one of the first textbooks on Bayesian statistics, which assess the uncertainty of future outcomes by incorporating new evidence as it arises, rather than relying on historical data. He also wrote numerous papers on multistage decision-making.}}</ref> |- valign="top" | [[Calyampudi Radhakrishna Rao|Rao, Calyampudi Radhakrishna]] || Indian || 1920 || || Co-developed [[Cramér–Rao bound]] and [[Rao–Blackwell theorem]], invented [[MINQUE]] method of variance component estimation. || <ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1214/ss/1177013438 | title = A Conversation with C. R. Rao | year = 1987 | author = Degroot, Morris H. | journal = Statistical Science | volume = 2 | pages = 53–67}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | url = http://www.amstat.org/about/statisticiansinhistory/index.cfm?fuseaction=biosinfo&BioID=13 | title = Rao, Calyampudi R| publisher = [[American Statistical Association]] |work = Statisticians in History }}</ref> |- valign="top" | [[David Cox (statistician)|Cox, David]] || English || 1924 || || Developed the [[proportional hazards model]] for the analysis of [[survival analysis|survival data]] || <ref>{{cite book |author1=Wermuth, Nanny |author2=Anthony C. Davison |author3=Dodge, Yadolah | title = Celebrating Statistics: Papers in honour of Sir David Cox on his 80th birthday (Oxford Statistical Science Series) | publisher = Oxford University Press | year = 2005 | isbn = 0-19-856654-9 | oclc = 185035518 }}</ref> |- valign="top" | [[Bradley Efron|Efron, Bradley]] || American || 1938 || || Invented the [[Bootstrapping (statistics)|bootstrap resampling technique]] for deriving an empirical distribution of an estimate of a model parameter || <ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1214/ss/1063994967 | title = Introduction to the Silver Anniversary of the Bootstrap | year = 2003 | author = Casella, George | journal = Statistical Science | volume = 18 | pages = 133–134 | issue = 2}}</ref> |}
